{"ts": "2026-06-21T13:41:36.581", "level": "INFO", "event": "llm_response", "stage": "stage4_narrate", "model": "physics-solver-llm", "elapsed_ms": 17551, "attempt": 1, "response_chars": 1773, "prompt_tokens": 996, "completion_tokens": 648, "total_tokens": 1644, "response_preview": "1. The problem involves calculating the electrostatic force between two point charges placed in vacuum. We start by identifying the correct equation to use, which is Coulomb's Law: \\( F = \\frac{q_1 q_2}{4 \\pi \\epsilon_0 r^2} \\). This law states that the magnitude of the force between two point charges is directly proportional to the product of their magnitudes and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.\n\n2. We substitute the given values into the equation: \\( q_1 = 2 \\mu C = 2 \\times 10^{-6} C \\), \\( q_2 = 3 \\mu C = 3 \\times 10^{-6} C \\), and \\( r = 0.5 m \\). The value of the vacuum permittivity constant, \\( \\epsilon_0 \\), is approximately \\( 8.854 \\times 10^{-12} F/m \\).\n\n3. Substituting these values into Coulomb's Law gives us: \n   \\[\n   F = \\frac{(2 \\times 10^{-6})(3 \\times 10^{-6})}{4 \\pi (8.854 \\times 10^{-12})(0.5)^2}\n   \\]\n   Simplifying the numerator and denominator:\n   \\[\n   F = \\frac{6 \\times 10^{-12}}{4 \\pi (8.854 \\times 10^{-12}) (0.25)}\n   \\]\n   "}
